\"http://schema.org/Review\"\u003e\n  \u003clink itemprop=\"url\" href=\"https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/37822903\" /\u003e\n  \u003ca title=\"Anne\" class=\"left imgcol\" href=\"/user/show/1720620-anne\"\u003e\u003cimg alt=\"Anne\" src=\"https://d.gr-assets.com/users/1415374035p2/1720620.jpg\" /\u003e\u003c/a\u003e\n\n  \u003cdiv class=\"left bodycol\"\u003e\n    \u003cdiv class=\"reviewHeader uitext stacked\"\u003e\n        \u003ca class=\"reviewDate createdAt right\" itemprop=\"publishDate\" href=\"/review/show/37822903?book_show_action=false\"\u003eOct 10, 2015\u003c/a\u003e\n\n      \u003ca title=\"Anne\" class=\"user\" href=\"/user/show/1720620-anne\"\u003eAnne\u003c/a\u003e\n\n        rated it\n        \u003cspan class=\" staticStars\"\u003e\u003cspan title=\"it was amazing\" size=\"15x15\" class=\"staticStar p10\"\u003eit was amazing\u003c/span\u003e\u003cspan title=\"it was amazing\" size=\"15x15\" class=\"staticStar p10\"\u003e\u003c/span\u003e\u003cspan title=\"it was amazing\" size=\"15x15\" class=\"staticStar p10\"\u003e\u003c/span\u003e\u003cspan title=\"it was amazing\" size=\"15x15\" class=\"staticStar p10\"\u003e\u003c/span\u003e\u003cspan title=\"it was amazing\" size=\"15x15\" class=\"staticStar p10\"\u003e\u003c/span\u003e\u003c/span\u003e\n\n\n          \u003cdiv\u003e\u003cspan class=\"uitext greyText\"\u003eRecommends it for: \u003c/span\u003e\n           \u003cspan class=\"uitext reviewText\"\u003ejill joyce\u003c/span\u003e\u003c/div\u003e\n\n        \n\n\n          \u003cdiv class=\"uitext greyText bookshelves\"\u003e\n            Shelves:\n              \u003ca class=\"actionLinkLite\" href=\"/review/list/1720620-anne?shelf=paranormal\"\u003eparanormal\u003c/a\u003e, \n              \u003ca class=\"actionLinkLite\" href=\"/review/list/1720620-anne?shelf=romance\"\u003eromance\u003c/a\u003e, \n              \u003ca class=\"actionLinkLite\" href=\"/review/list/1720620-anne?shelf=read-in-2009\"\u003eread-in-2009\u003c/a\u003e, \n              \u003ca class=\"actionLinkLite\" href=\"/review/list/1720620-anne?shelf=young-adult\"\u003eyoung-adult\u003c/a\u003e, \n              \u003ca class=\"actionLinkLite\" href=\"/review/list/1720620-anne?shelf=favorites\"\u003efavorites\u003c/a\u003e\n          \u003c/div\u003e\n    \u003c/div\u003e\n\n\n        \u003cdiv class=\"reviewText stacked\"\u003e\n              \u003cspan id=\"reviewTextContainer37822903\" class=\"readable\" style=\"\"\u003e\n            \n\u003cspan id=\"freeTextContainer5648887550867129217\"\u003eI loved this book. There. I said it. In fact, I loved the whole series. What can I say? It was a totally unbelievable paranormal love story, filled with way too much drama and teenage angst. And I loved it. Why?\u003cbr\u003eThe series reminds me of \"fair food\". You know, the food you buy when you go to a state fair or carnival? You know you shouldn't want to eat that stuff. And somewhere in your head there is a little voice telling you that it was prepared by someone who hasn't washed their hands in days, bu\u003c/span\u003e\n  \u003cspan id=\"freeText5648887550867129217\" style=\"display:none\"\u003eI loved this book. There. I said it. In fact, I loved the whole series. What can I say? It was a totally unbelievable paranormal love story, filled with way too much drama and teenage angst. And I loved it. Why?\u003cbr\u003eThe series reminds me of \"fair food\". You know, the food you buy when you go to a state fair or carnival? You know you shouldn't want to eat that stuff. And somewhere in your head there is a little voice telling you that it was prepared by someone who hasn't washed their hands in days, but you eat it anyway. Not only do you eat it, but you look forward to eating more. Deep fried corn dogs, greasy pizza, funnel cakes, and elephant ears...yum! The way I see it, everyone could use a little cotton candy from the circus. Read the books. Life is too short not to eat the creamy Velveeta cheese of The Twilight Saga.\u003c/span\u003e\n  \u003ca data-text-id=\"5648887550867129217\" href=\"#\" onclick=\"swapContent($(this));; return false;\"\u003e...more\u003c/a\u003e\n\n          \u003c/span\u003e\n        \u003c/div\u003e\n\n\n      \u003cdiv class=\"reviewFooter uitext buttons\"\u003e\n        \n\n\u003ctr class=\"no_border feedFooterReview\" id=\"update_comment_stuff_Review37822903\"\u003e\n  \u003ctd colspan=\"2\"\u003e\n    \u003cdiv class=\"updateActionLinks\"\u003e\n        \u003ca class=\"right flag\" rel=\"nofollow\" id=\"flag_link37822903\" title=\"Flag this review as inappropriate.\" href=\"/flagged/new?resource_id=37822903\u0026amp;resource_type=Review\u0026amp;return_url=%2Fbook%2Fshow%2F41865.Twilight\"\u003eflag\u003c/a\u003e\n\n\n\n\n\n      \u003cspan class='likeItContainer' id='like_container_review_37822903'\u003e\u003ca id=\"like_count_review_37822903\" rel=\"nofollow\" href=\"/rating/voters/37822903?resource_type=Review\"\u003e\u003cspan class=\"likesCount\"\u003e59 likes\u003c/span\u003e\u003c/a\u003e\u0026nbsp;\u0026middot;\u0026nbsp;\u003ca rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"jsLike like_it gr-button gr-button--small\" href=\"https://www.goodreads.com/user/new?remember=true\u0026amp;return_url=%2Fbook%2Freviews%2F41865\"\u003eLike\u003c/a\u003e\u003c/span\u003e\u0026nbsp;\u0026middot;\u0026nbsp;\u003ca href=\"/review/show/37822903?book_show_action=false\u0026amp;from_review_page=2\"\u003esee review\u003c/a\u003e\n    \u003c/div\u003e\n\n\n    \u003cdiv id='comments_for_review_37822903' style='display: none;'\u003e\n\u003cdiv class='brown_comment'\u003e\n\u003cspan class=\"loadingLinkSpan\"\u003e\u003ca class=\"loadingLink\" data-remote=\"true\" href=\"/review/37822903/comments?reverse=true\"\u003eView all 106 comments\u003c/a\u003e\u003cspan class=\"loadingAnimation\"\u003e\u003c/span\u003e\u003cspan class=\"loadingError\"\u003e\u003c/span\u003e\u003c/span\u003e\n\u003c/div\u003e\n\n\u003c/div\u003e\n\n  \u003c/td\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\n      \u003c/div\u003e\n\n  \u003c/div\u003e\n\n  \u003cdiv class=\"clear\"\u003e\u003c/div\u003e\n\u003c/div\u003e\n\n    \u003c/div\u003e\n  \u003c/div\u003e\n    \u003cdiv class=\"elementListBrownSeparator\"\u003e\u003c/div\u003e\n\n\n\n  \u003cdiv class=\"friendReviews elementListBrown\"\u003e\n    \u003cdiv class=\"section\"\u003e\n      \n\n\u003cdiv id=\"review_22793170\" class=\"review\" itemprop=\"reviews\" itemscope itemtype=\"http://schema.org/Review\"\u003e\n  \u003clink itemprop=\"url\" href=\"https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/22793170\" /\u003e\n  \u003ca title=\"Natalie\" class=\"left imgcol\" href=\"/user/show/1181505-natalie\"\u003e\u003cimg alt=\"Natalie\" src=\"https://d.gr-assets.com/users/1211516369p2/1181505.jpg\" /\u003e\u003c/a\u003e\n\n  \u003cdiv class=\"left bodycol\"\u003e\n    \u003cdiv class=\"reviewHeader uitext stacked\"\u003e\n        \u003ca class=\"reviewDate createdAt right\" itemprop=\"publishDate\" href=\"/review/show/22793170?book_show_action=false\"\u003eMay 22, 2008\u003c/a\u003e\n\n      \u003ca title=\"Natalie\" class=\"user\" href=\"/user/show/1181505-natalie\"\u003eNatalie\u003c/a\u003e\n\n        rated it\n        \u003cspan class=\" staticStars\"\u003e\u003cspan title=\"did not like it\" size=\"15x15\" class=\"staticStar p10\"\u003edid not like it\u003c/span\u003e\u003cspan title=\"did not like it\" size=\"15x15\" class=\"staticStar p0\"\u003e\u003c/span\u003e\u003cspan title=\"did not like it\" size=\"15x15\" class=\"staticStar p0\"\u003e\u003c/span\u003e\u003cspan title=\"did not like it\" size=\"15x15\" class=\"staticStar p0\"\u003e\u003c/span\u003e\u003cspan title=\"did not like it\" size=\"15x15\" class=\"staticStar p0\"\u003e\u003c/span\u003e\u003c/span\u003e\n\n          \u003cspan class=\"greyText\"\u003e\u0026nbsp;\u0026middot;\u0026nbsp;\u003c/span\u003e\n          \u003ca class=\"lightGreyText\" title=\"Paperback 9780316058988\" href=\"/book/show/12024.Twilight\"\u003ereview of another edition\u003c/a\u003e\n\n\n        \n\n\n          \u003cdiv class=\"uitext greyText bookshelves\"\u003e\n            Shelves:\n              \u003ca class=\"actionLinkLite\" href=\"/review/list/1181505-natalie?shelf=chick-lit\"\u003echick-lit\u003c/a\u003e, \n              \u003ca class=\"actionLinkLite\" href=\"/review/list/1181505-natalie?shelf=ya-lit\"\u003eya-lit\u003c/a\u003e\n          \u003c/div\u003e\n    \u003c/div\u003e\n\n\n        \u003cdiv class=\"reviewText stacked\"\u003e\n              \u003cspan id=\"reviewTextContainer22793170\" class=\"readable\" style=\"\"\u003e\n            \n\u003cspan id=\"freeTextContainer6622421776708473415\"\u003eMy roommate has been telling me for years that I like to go contrary public opinion. If the world likes a movie, I will hate it. If the world hates a television program, it will quickly become my favorite. I don’t agree with her over all analysis, I mean I love Harry Potter, The Office, and many other popular things. Of course I also thought that The Da Vinci Code wasn’t as good of a book as everyone else thought it was and I am still not sure if Studio 60 on the Sunset Strip should have gone of\u003c/span\u003e\n  \u003cspan id=\"freeText6622421776708473415\" style=\"display:none\"\u003eMy roommate has been telling me for years that I like to go contrary public opinion. If the world likes a movie, I will hate it. If the world hates a television program, it will quickly become my favorite. I don’t agree with her over all analysis, I mean I love Harry Potter, The Office, and many other popular things. Of course I also thought that The Da Vinci Code wasn’t as good of a book as everyone else thought it was and I am still not sure if Studio 60 on the Sunset Strip should have gone off the air, even if I was about its only viewer. So maybe my roommate was right. Maybe I am prejudice against what most people like. The problem is when I picked up Twlight by Stephenie Meyers I wanted to like it. I had been hearing about it for years, my sister is constantly reading it and I am fielding complaint letters at work that we carry it (usually that is a good sign that the book is good, no really it is) so though I had resisted the popular nature of the book I was secretly pleased when my book club decided to read it.\u003cbr\u003e\u003cbr\u003eGuess what, I hated the book. No really hated it. So E, remember back when we did our Harry Potter review you wondered what would happen if I read and reviewed a book I didn’t like? Well you get to find out now.\u003cbr\u003e\u003cbr\u003eFor those of you who have missed the Twilight mania currently sweeping the nation (my sister boasts she was one of the first Twilighters) it is the story of Bella, a 17 year old girl who relocates to Forks, Washington after her mother remarries. She is miserable there and longs for the sun and warmth of Phoenix. But then she meets fellow 17 year old Edward Cullen. She is drawn to Edward for some reason, though he seems to absolutely despise her. As the weeks go by she gains new friends and settles into a routine in her new town, which includes wondering why Edward hates her so much. Of course he finally begins talking to her, and we find out he is love in with her. There are several events that lead up to the big reveal, but the reader isn’t surprised by this Lizzy/Darcy relationship. Of course there are mysteries surrounding Edward, mysteries that Bella is determined to solve. And guess what she finds out he is a vampire!!!!\u003cbr\u003e\u003cbr\u003eOkay so yeah that is the story in less than 144 words. Of course there are trials and tribulations that Bella and Edward face after this big revelation. Bella compares them to a modern day ‘Romeo and Juliet’ something that made me gag every time it was alluded too. I must say Meyers got the one dimensional love sick teenager down to a tee. Then there is the brooding, Heathcliff type, Edward. Good looking, dangerous, dark, mysterious, I am not quite sure what he sees in immature Bella, maybe we will find out in the next book. He is one of the few well rounded characters in the book. Though his struggle and flip flopping get old after 200 pages (the book is 500).\u003cbr\u003e\u003cbr\u003eThe story is trite. In fact nothing happens until page 378 and then you get about 50-55 pages of great story, interesting, fast past, oh my gosh I can’t stop reading and then it is over and you are back to the boring and the mundane. For the last 60 or so pages. Where is more of the hemming and hawing you had to endure for the first 377 pages.\u003cbr\u003e\u003cbr\u003eI knew I should have given up when it took me three days to get through the first chapter. When I was a week into reading and hadn’t even made it half way through. When I picked up an old text book and started reading it.\u003cbr\u003e\u003cbr\u003eNow I didn’t expect this to be Faulkner, or Austen, or Fitzgerald. I didn’t even expect this to be Rowling, I expected your average book that would be a quick and fun read. I read those all the time. I read any trade mystery I can get my hands on and love it even more if there is a splash of romance, but this makes me shiver. The writing is juvenile, I have read online fanfic writers who are better wordsmith’s than Ms. Meyers. The story non existent, and there are no redeeming qualities in the main character.\u003cbr\u003e\u003cbr\u003eThe one thing that saves this book (besides the 55 pages of actual story and decent writing) is the support cast. I really liked Edward’s mom and sister. I wanted to see more of them, learn more about them. But of course they were simple bystanders that I had to wonder about. There were things that were never explained (maybe they are in the sequels, but I don’t think I will ever find out) and so many plot holes I was ready to tear my hair out.\u003cbr\u003e\u003cbr\u003eSo maybe my roommate is right. Maybe I am destined to never like anything that is pop culture. I mean who am I to argue with The New York Times, Scholastic Book Review, and my little sister- oh yeah, usually the first in line.\u003cbr\u003e\u003cbr\u003e1 ½ stars- because those 55 pages were actually good and at least it is getting students to read. That is better than nothing.\u003c/span\u003e\n  \u003ca data-text-id=\"6622421776708473415\" href=\"#\" onclick=\"swapContent($(this));; return false;\"\u003e...more\u003c/a\u003e\n\n          \u003c/span\u003e\n        \u003c/div\u003e\n\n\n      \u003cdiv class=\"reviewFooter uitext buttons\"\u003e\n        \n\n\u003ctr class=\"no_border feedFooterReview\" id=\"update_comment_stuff_Review22793170\"\u003e\n  \u003ctd colspan=\"2\"\u003e\n    \u003cdiv class=\"updateActionLinks\"\u003e\n        \u003ca class=\"right flag\" rel=\"nofollow\" id=\"flag_link22793170\" title=\"Flag this review as inappropriate.\" href=\"/flagged/new?resource_id=22793170\u0026amp;resource_type=Review\u0026amp;return_url=%2Fbook%2Fshow%2F41865.Twilight\"\u003eflag\u003c/a\u003e\n\n\n\n\n\n      \u003cspan class='likeItContainer' id='like_container_review_22793170'\u003e\u003ca id=\"like_count_review_22793170\" rel=\"nofollow\" href=\"/rating/voters/22793170?resource_type=Review\"\u003e\u003cspan class=\"likesCount\"\u003e57 likes\u003c/span\u003e\u003c/a\u003e\u0026nbsp;\u0026middot;\u0026nbsp;\u003ca rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"jsLike like_it gr-button gr-button--small\" href=\"https://www.goodreads.com/user/new?remember=true\u0026amp;return_url=%2Fbook%2Freviews%2F41865\"\u003eLike\u003c/a\u003e\u003c/span\u003e\u0026nbsp;\u0026middot;\u0026nbsp;\u003ca href=\"/review/show/22793170?book_show_action=false\u0026amp;from_review_page=2\"\u003esee review\u003c/a\u003e\n    \u003c/div\u003e\n\n\n    \u003cdiv id='comments_for_review_22793170' style='display: none;'\u003e\n\u003cdiv class='brown_comment'\u003e\n\u003cspan class=\"loadingLinkSpan\"\u003e\u003ca class=\"loadingLink\" data-remote=\"true\" href=\"/review/22793170/comments?reverse=true\"\u003eView all 11 comments\u003c/a\u003e\u003cspan class=\"loadingAnimation\"\u003e\u003c/span\u003e\u003cspan class=\"loadingError\"\u003e\u003c/span\u003e\u003c/span\u003e\n\u003c/div\u003e\n\n\u003c/div\u003e\n\n  \u003c/td\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\n      \u003c/div\u003e\n\n  \u003c/div\u003e\n\n  \u003cdiv class=\"clear\"\u003e\u003c/div\u003e\n\u003c/div\u003e\n\n    \u003c/div\u003e\n  \u003c/div\u003e\n    \u003cdiv class=\"elementListBrownSeparator\"\u003e\u003c/div\u003e\n\n\n\n  \u003cdiv class=\"friendReviews elementListBrown\"\u003e\n    \u003cdiv class=\"section\"\u003e\n      \n\n\u003cdiv id=\"review_65033746\" class=\"review\" itemprop=\"reviews\" itemscope itemtype=\"http://schema.org/Review\"\u003e\n  \u003clink itemprop=\"url\" href=\"https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/65033746\" /\u003e\n  \u003ca title=\"Bram\" class=\"left imgcol\" href=\"/user/show/1797553-bram\"\u003e\u003cimg alt=\"Bram\" src=\"https://d.gr-assets.com/users/1253845069p2/1797553.jpg\" /\u003e\u003c/a\u003e\n\n  \u003cdiv class=\"left bodycol\"\u003e\n    \u003cdiv class=\"reviewHeader uitext stacked\"\u003e\n        \u003ca class=\"reviewDate createdAt right\" itemprop=\"publishDate\" href=\"/review/show/65033746?book_show_action=false\"\u003eDec 03, 2013\u003c/a\u003e\n\n      \u003ca title=\"Bram\" class=\"user\" href=\"/user/show/1797553-bram\"\u003eBram\u003c/a\u003e\n\n        rated it\n        \u003cspan class=\" staticStars\"\u003e\u003cspan title=\"it was ok\" size=\"15x15\" class=\"staticStar p10\"\u003eit was ok\u003c/span\u003e\u003cspan title=\"it was ok\" size=\"15x15\" class=\"staticStar p10\"\u003e\u003c/span\u003e\u003cspan title=\"it was ok\" size=\"15x15\" class=\"staticStar p0\"\u003e\u003c/span\u003e\u003cspan title=\"it was ok\" size=\"15x15\" class=\"staticStar p0\"\u003e\u003c/span\u003e\u003cspan title=\"it was ok\" size=\"15x15\" class=\"staticStar p0\"\u003e\u003c/span\u003e\u003c/span\u003e\n\n\n\n        \n\n\n          \u003cdiv class=\"uitext greyText bookshelves\"\u003e\n            Shelves:\n              \u003ca class=\"actionLinkLite\" href=\"/review/list/1797553-bram?shelf=2009\"\u003e2009\u003c/a\u003e\n          \u003c/div\u003e\n    \u003c/div\u003e\n\n\n        \u003cdiv class=\"reviewText stacked\"\u003e\n              \u003cspan id=\"reviewTextContainer65033746\" class=\"readable\" style=\"\"\u003e\n            \n\u003cspan id=\"freeTextContainer3345264047424218020\"\u003eFor series genre books, I think the ultimate test of enjoyment is simple—it’s when the current book you’re reading makes you want to read the next one. And I think this desire needs to be reasonably reflected in the subjective star rating. Now I've seen bookshelves with all four \u003cem\u003eTwilight\u003c/em\u003e books marked “read” and only \u003cem\u003efive stars\u003c/em\u003e between them. Dear Goodreaders, am I in the wrong to believe that this is axiomatically disingenuous? I know there's often some difficulty in weighing one’s subjective res\u003c/span\u003e\n  \u003cspan id=\"freeText3345264047424218020\" style=\"display:none\"\u003eFor series genre books, I think the ultimate test of enjoyment is simple—it’s when the current book you’re reading makes you want to read the next one. And I think this desire needs to be reasonably reflected in the subjective star rating. Now I've seen bookshelves with all four \u003cem\u003eTwilight\u003c/em\u003e books marked “read” and only \u003cem\u003efive stars\u003c/em\u003e between them. Dear Goodreaders, am I in the wrong to believe that this is axiomatically disingenuous? I know there's often some difficulty in weighing one’s subjective response (or lack thereof), particularly when a book has much to be admired or, more relevant in this case, little to be admired. And Goodreads certainly doesn’t make things any easier by failing to address the obvious need for half stars. But giving a book one star and then continuing a series that you ostensibly hate for another 1500 pages? I don't buy it. So anyway the truth is that I \u003cem\u003ekind of\u003c/em\u003e am almost mildly sort of interested in reading the next one. Therefore, this book is already at two stars. If I go forward with \u003cem\u003eHalf Moon: Chess Piece\u003c/em\u003e or whatever book two is called (I’m guessing here based on rushed glances into airport “bookstores”), then I promise I will bump this up to three stars out of a dedication to ratings fairness...and then do whatever is necessary for absolution. I certainly won’t claim that this book deserves two or three stars—something that will become increasingly obvious below—but I did tear through the last 100+ pages (after the baseball thunderstorm game—don’t ask) before immediately watching the movie On Demand, by myself, on a Saturday night. I understand that this confession is grounds for many Goodreads friends to begin hiding their last names and emails \u003cem\u003estat\u003c/em\u003e. So be it. \u003cbr\u003e\u003cbr\u003eConsidering the setting and subject matter of this book, the fact that I frequently found myself engrossed is beyond terrifying (petty high school drama piques my interest? Really? \u003cstrong\u003eFuck.\u003c/strong\u003e) and is mostly responsible for my inability to face reviewing this for so long. But let’s start with the somewhat objective good here. One thing I wasn't necessarily expecting is the disturbingly realistic picture of white middle class banality that makes up the early portion of the book. It's the one thing Meyer seems to pull off well, although I can’t decide on her intent or the degree to which she tried to push this theme. Obviously we’re supposed to see Edward the very white knight rescue Bella the very white damsel from her very, very white suburban high school hell. Or are we? I’m just going to go ahead and give Meyer credit for subtly satirizing dull, white, meaningless existence even though this is a well-traveled road and she’s probably not even traveling it. Plus 1.5 (take that, Goodreads!) stars. \u003cbr\u003e\u003cbr\u003eOk, the bad. All of Edward's smirking, mocking, demeaning, chortling, snorting, chuckling, snickering, sniggering, sneering, and condescending will inevitably induce (or your money back) a reverie in which Wesley Snipes uses every weapon invented in the last three millennia to slaughter livid, spiky-toothed Alexander McQueen models with a degree of fury and vengeance that makes the Old Testament look like a Mr. Rodgers episode. Someone needs to call Stephenie Meyer \u003cem\u003estat\u003c/em\u003e and explain to her that audible mirth is called laughing, and that when you try to add variety with snickering, chortling, snorting, chuckling, et al. you sure as hell better be spoofing ludicrous bad guy stereotypes. But these laughing variants are all credited to Edward, who has obviously been studying Neg Theory and Routines (\u003ca href=\"http://www.seductionbase.com/neg-theory.htm\" rel=\"nofollow\"\u003ewww.seductionbase.com/neg-theory.htm\u003c/a\u003e) since 1921 (yes, he's really old and proof that maturity comes from a degenerating body, not age). Edward doesn’t just chuckle and snicker though. He chuckles and snickers \u003cem\u003eentire sentences\u003c/em\u003e. As in, “blah blah blah blah blah you have no idea how blah blah dangerous I blah am,” Edward snickered. I wish I still had a copy of this book to get a real quote, but I promise there's very little paraphrasing here. \u003cbr\u003e\u003cbr\u003eAnd this is going to make me sound like your mother, but I don't really give a shit because an entire generation of girls (many of whom are young enough to have ZERO experience in dating) worships a book in which the hero not only treats the heroine like an utterly scorn-worthy creature, but also must save her from every single danger and inconvenience in her life, except for the danger of poor self-esteem since he's hell-bent on humiliating her at every opportunity with snarky comments and scathing glances. Now Meyer gives Edward an easy target by making it clear from chapter one that Bella has some sort of cerebellum disorder that leaves her in a constant state of vertigo, tripping, and man-worshiping that places her at enormous risk for rape, car accidents, gym class embarrassments, and probably autodefenestration. \u003cbr\u003e\u003cbr\u003eFurther justification for Edward's assholery emerges when Meyer tells us that this is just the understandable lashing out of someone eternally denied his true biological yearnings. He's grumpy because he can’t tear open Bella's flesh and suck her dry when he's thirsty. Who can't relate to that? To make things worse, neither can he tear open Bella’s dress and yadda yadda yadda, although the lu*t thing seems to be a bigger problem for our clumsy heroine. This gets me back to the man-worship. Even if you haven’t read the book, you’ve probably heard/read what you \u003cem\u003ethought\u003c/em\u003e to be hyperbole on the number of times Bella uses “perfect” to describe Edward’s face, and to a lesser degree his hairless white man-body. Let me be clear: it is almost \u003cem\u003eimpossible\u003c/em\u003e to exaggerate the absurdity of this aspect of the book. In fact, I’ve enlisted a certain Mr. Kowalski to provide an exact tally of these instances for statistical purposes, assuming he has what it takes to see this book to the end (subtle strategy, I know). Of course, “perfect” is a horribly useless description of almost anything and—always ready to give the benefit of the doubt—I will simply assume that Meyer’s thesaurus ended somewhere between “lau-” and “per-”. But props to her for giving each boy and girl reader the chance to imagine their very own version of the perfect, perfectly-Aryan man-face. Or maybe she just wanted to leave Hollywood studios with maximum creative casting possibilities. \u003cbr\u003e\u003cbr\u003eMy motherly objections to the book are, in fact, terribly ironic considering how gleeful so many parents must be that their children are reading books (yay!) in which the hero and heroine revel in self-satisfied smugness over their precious co-virginity (yay!!). Since the anti-s*x messages have been thoroughly explored at this point, I decided to try very hard to take this aspect of the story at face value, which did ultimately enhance my enjoyment. The more I think about it now though, the s*x thing is basically a cheat because it allows Meyer to get the utmost from intimacy while having a ready excuse to eliminate s*x. This keeps things acceptable for the very young while still managing to entice older readers for whom romantic intimacy has been relegated to (doctored) memories. But once you block out the fact that the essential conundrum of the book is an allegory strong enough to make \u003cem\u003eThe Chronicles of Narnia\u003c/em\u003e appear ambiguous, you can see Meyer succeed in adding a new twist to an ancient storyline—that of tragic romantic love. \u003cbr\u003e\u003cbr\u003eWhich leads me into my theory on the popularity of this book. Let me preface this with an apology in the case that I’m the 179th reviewer to point this out. Meyer takes the key elements from two of the most popular romantic stories ever told and packages them into shiny, upper elementary gloriousness. This is like the vampire romance genre equivalent of what Christopher Paolini did by transferring the exact plot of \u003cem\u003eStar Wars\u003c/em\u003e into dragon fantasy (or so I’ve been told). First, we have Edward cast in the role of Mr. Darcy. While reasons are given for Darcy and Edward being dicks to their heroines for much of their respective books, I’d like to point out that this isn't really excusable. It's also pure fantasy. If a guy treats you like shit for a while only to subsequently fall in love with you and start being nice, you better believe that he's going to be treating you like shit again in 10 years. (As a man who’s been married for almost two weeks, I have all sorts of great, reliable advice like this—just send me a private message). Regardless, I suppose there’s nothing more alluring than a story about a rich, beautiful dickhead who you (erm, the heroine) convert into a loving, kind, passionate, and very rich husband. Stephenie took that one to the bank; high fives all around. The second key to success is more generic: instead of Montagues and Capulets, we get Humans and Vampires. Damned if you do, damned if you don’t. Obviou$ but effective. \u003cbr\u003e\u003cbr\u003eAnd lastly, to preempt the inevitable catcalls, let me state that this review is a shameless attempt to garner votes. I should also note that this statement is itself a shameless attempt to garner votes. And that second statement was an attempt at humor…which was a shameless attempt to garner votes. (Am I covered?) \u003c/span\u003e\n  \u003ca data-text-id=\"3345264047424218020\" href=\"#\" onclick=\"swapContent($(this));; return false;\"\u003e...more\u003c/a\u003e\n\n          \u003c/span\u003e\n        \u003c/div\u003e\n\n\n      \u003cdiv class=\"reviewFooter uitext buttons\"\u003e\n        \n\n\u003ctr class=\"no_border feedFooterReview\" id=\"update_comment_stuff_Review65033746\"\u003e\n  \u003ctd colspan=\"2\"\u003e\n    \u003cdiv class=\"updateActionLinks\"\u003e\n        \u003ca class=\"right flag\" rel=\"nofollow\" id=\"flag_link65033746\" title=\"Flag this review as inappropriate.\" href=\"/flagged/new?resource_id=65033746\u0026amp;resource_type=Review\u0026amp;return_url=%2Fbook%2Fshow%2F41865.Twilight\"\u003eflag\u003c/a\u003e\n\n\n\n\n\n      \u003cspan class='likeItContainer' id='like_container_review_65033746'\u003e\u003ca id=\"like_count_review_65033746\" rel=\"nofollow\" href=\"/rating/voters/65033746?resource_type=Review\"\u003e\u003cspan class=\"likesCount\"\u003e53 likes\u003c/span\u003e\u003c/a\u003e\u0026nbsp;\u0026middot;\u0026nbsp;\u003ca rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"jsLike like_it gr-button gr-button--small\" href=\"https://www.goodreads.com/user/new?remember=true\u0026amp;return_url=%2Fbook%2Freviews%2F41865\"\u003eLike\u003c/a\u003e\u003c/span\u003e\u0026nbsp;\u0026middot;\u0026nbsp;\u003ca href=\"/review/show/65033746?book_show_action=false\u0026amp;from_review_page=2\"\u003esee review\u003c/a\u003e\n    \u003c/div\u003e\n\n\n    \u003cdiv id='comments_for_review_65033746' style='display: none;'\u003e\n\u003cdiv class='brown_comment'\u003e\n\u003cspan class=\"loadingLinkSpan\"\u003e\u003ca class=\"loadingLink\" data-remote=\"true\" href=\"/review/65033746/comments?reverse=true\"\u003eView all 116 comments\u003c/a\u003e\u003cspan class=\"loadingAnimation\"\u003e\u003c/span\u003e\u003cspan class=\"loadingError\"\u003e\u003c/span\u003e\u003c/span\u003e\n\u003c/div\u003e\n\n\u003c/div\u003e\n\n  \u003c/td\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\n      \u003c/div\u003e\n\n  \u003c/div\u003e\n\n  \u003cdiv class=\"clear\"\u003e\u003c/div\u003e\n\u003c/div\u003e\n\n    \u003c/div\u003e\n  \u003c/div\u003e\n    \u003cdiv class=\"elementListBrownSeparator\"\u003e\u003c/div\u003e\n\n\n\n  \u003cdiv class=\"friendReviews elementListBrown\"\u003e\n    \u003cdiv class=\"section\"\u003e\n      \n\n\u003cdiv id=\"review_22546263\" class=\"review nosyndicate\" itemprop=\"reviews\" itemscope itemtype=\"http://schema.org/Review\"\u003e\n  \u003clink itemprop=\"url\" href=\"https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/22546263\" /\u003e\n  \u003ca title=\"Siyuan\" class=\"left imgcol\" href=\"/user/show/149400-siyuan\"\u003e\u003cimg alt=\"Siyuan\" src=\"https://s.gr-assets.com/assets/nophoto/user/f_50x66-6a03a5c12233c941481992b82eea8d23.png\" /\u003e\u003c/a\u003e\n\n  \u003cdiv class=\"left bodycol\"\u003e\n    \u003cdiv class=\"reviewHeader uitext stacked\"\u003e\n        \u003ca class=\"reviewDate createdAt right\" itemprop=\"publishDate\" href=\"/review/show/22546263?book_show_action=false\"\u003eNov 14, 2009\u003c/a\u003e\n\n      \u003ca title=\"Siyuan\" class=\"user\" href=\"/user/show/149400-siyuan\"\u003eSiyuan\u003c/a\u003e\n\n        rated it\n        \u003cspan class=\" staticStars\"\u003e\u003cspan title=\"did not like it\" size=\"15x15\" class=\"staticStar p10\"\u003edid not like it\u003c/span\u003e\u003cspan title=\"did not like it\" size=\"15x15\" class=\"staticStar p0\"\u003e\u003c/span\u003e\u003cspan title=\"did not like it\" size=\"15x15\" class=\"staticStar p0\"\u003e\u003c/span\u003e\u003cspan title=\"did not like it\" size=\"15x15\" class=\"staticStar p0\"\u003e\u003c/span\u003e\u003cspan title=\"did not like it\" size=\"15x15\" class=\"staticStar p0\"\u003e\u003c/span\u003e\u003c/span\u003e\n\n\n\n        \n\n\n          \u003cdiv class=\"uitext greyText bookshelves\"\u003e\n            Shelves:\n              \u003ca class=\"actionLinkLite\" href=\"/review/list/149400-siyuan?shelf=unrecommended\"\u003eunrecommended\u003c/a\u003e\n          \u003c/div\u003e\n    \u003c/div\u003e\n\n\n        \u003cdiv class=\"reviewText stacked\"\u003e\n              \u003cspan id=\"reviewTextContainer22546263\" class=\"readable\" style=\"\"\u003e\n            \n\u003cspan id=\"freeTextContainer8075445973990980153\"\u003eWhere to even begin. Books like this (along with the Da Vinci Code, that Eragon series) infuriate me. I have never seen any reason to shun any genre or plot devices, because good writing and narrative talent can make reading anything a pleasure. That said, Meyer's series is dull, at times laughable, unstructured, unoriginal, and just badly written, hopelessly falling short of realizing any of fiction's potential. to be fair, her writing isn't as atrocious as that of dan brown's and whatever that\u003c/span\u003e\n  \u003cspan id=\"freeText8075445973990980153\" style=\"display:none\"\u003eWhere to even begin. Books like this (along with the Da Vinci Code, that Eragon series) infuriate me. I have never seen any reason to shun any genre or plot devices, because good writing and narrative talent can make reading anything a pleasure. That said, Meyer's series is dull, at times laughable, unstructured, unoriginal, and just badly written, hopelessly falling short of realizing any of fiction's potential. to be fair, her writing isn't as atrocious as that of dan brown's and whatever that dragon kid's name is. but that doesn't save her from being a grossly overhyped, weak example of something that's already been done, and done far better. as plotlines go, there've been more outrageous and ridiculous ones by far, but a well-executed book can withstand that. If teen (and adult) readers selected books not by their publicity and popularity, they would easily be able to find better examples of the same genre among other books that have to share shelf space with Twilight. \u003cbr\u003e\u003cbr\u003ethere were so many parts where i wanted to cry, but not because i was so very, very moved:\u003cbr\u003e\u003cbr\u003eafter only a few interactions, edward says things like \"bella, you don't even realize it but you're so much specialler and better and unusualler and different from every human on the planet. i can't solve this incredibly complex rubik's cube that is you.\" this is often the premise of having a hero/heroine/antagonist in a story. you want them to be different, to stand out somehow, to be special. the problem is that at the point in the book where edward starts saying these things, meyer hasn't actually given the reader any evidence at all that this is true of bella. the reader is in her head, so it's not like she can hide anything, and the only special thing about her is that she is the new girl in town, not as used to rain, and very clumsy and disdainful. the fact that meyer actually needs one character to explain to the reader how they should feel about the main character/first person narrator kind of gives it away, doesn't it?\u003cbr\u003e\u003cbr\u003eedward also says furiously things like: \"jacob must be punished, O beloved, divinest long-necked white bird. for he saideth that you're pretty. OMG, YOU'RE NOT PRETTY! you're a transcendentally beautiful cygnet, and so far beyond pretty that for him to call you pretty is like spitting on you so i have to go break his bones now. your blood smells good and i glitter, so i can't let anyone insult you so horrendously.\"\u003cbr\u003e\u003cbr\u003ebella: \"Don't hurt him, i'm sure he didn't mean it.\"\u003cbr\u003e\u003cbr\u003eedward: \"All right, but only because you say so, i'll let him live. but if he ever dares call you pretty again, i'll make him sorry.\"\u003cbr\u003e\u003cbr\u003eat this point, i wondered why meyer was showing any restraint at all, and why she wasn't having edward earnestly say things like \"Did it hurt, when you fell from heaven?\" with a straight face. and mean it. \u003cbr\u003e\u003cbr\u003ei can't even begin to understand what emotional mechanism is making this character and this writing seem attractive to the primarily heterosexual, young adult female readership. \u003cbr\u003e\u003cbr\u003ei think part of the guilty pleasure many young women (myself included) have gotten from several books comes from the appeal of the fictional characters, and sometimes from the romantic appeal of the male characters. it's embarrassing, but it's very often true. that said, the improbably-named \"bella swan\" herself as a character is nothing to look at, personality-wise. \u003cbr\u003e\u003cbr\u003emr. darcy's appeal: subdued and aloof, but passionate despite himself, and all of this Austen managed to convey with skill and restraint. howl, owner of the moving castle, is vain and cowardly and flamboyant, but a good writer makes all that somehow appealing! anne's gilbert is natural, genuine, the schoolboy chum who grows up fairly quickly to be a very respectable man. twelfth night's duke orsino is...not very inspiring, but viola-turned-dashing-cesario more than makes up for it (not technically a male, but whatever). across genres and historical periods, writers have managed to sketch out nuanced, compelling characters, from the rough, deeply, fallibly human to the fantastically, impossibly unattainable superhuman. but edward?\u003cbr\u003e\u003cbr\u003eedward glitters in the sun and says terrible, terrible lines that not even fictional vampires living in washington state should be allowed to utter. bella screams in terror while riding piggyback on her motor-velociraptor-cycle of a boyfriend, rolls her eyes at everyone in her town who's not a vampire, and angrily trips herself a lot. \u003c/span\u003e\n  \u003ca data-text-id=\"8075445973990980153\" href=\"#\" onclick=\"swapContent($(this));; return false;\"\u003e...more\u003c/a\u003e\n\n          \u003c/span\u003e\n        \u003c/div\u003e\n\n\n      \u003cdiv class=\"reviewFooter uitext buttons\"\u003e\n        \n\n\u003ctr class=\"no_border feedFooterReview\" id=\"update_comment_stuff_Review22546263\"\u003e\n  \u003ctd colspan=\"2\"\u003e\n    \u003cdiv class=\"updateActionLinks\"\u003e\n        \u003ca class=\"right flag\" rel=\"nofollow\" id=\"flag_link22546263\" title=\"Flag this review as inappropriate.\" href=\"/flagged/new?resource_id=22546263\u0026amp;resource_type=Review\u0026amp;return_url=%2Fbook%2Fshow%2F41865.Twilight\"\u003eflag\u003c/a\u003e\n\n\n\n\n\n      \u003cspan class='likeItContainer' id='like_container_review_22546263'\u003e\u003ca id=\"like_count_review_22546263\" rel=\"nofollow\" href=\"/rating/voters/22546263?resource_type=Review\"\u003e\u003cspan class=\"likesCount\"\u003e53 likes\u003c/span\u003e\u003c/a\u003e\u0026nbsp;\u0026middot;\u0026nbsp;\u003ca rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"jsLike like_it gr-button gr-button--small\" href=\"https://www.goodreads.com/user/new?remember=true\u0026amp;return_url=%2Fbook%2Freviews%2F41865\"\u003eLike\u003c/a\u003e\u003c/span\u003e\u0026nbsp;\u0026middot;\u0026nbsp;\u003ca href=\"/review/show/22546263?book_show_action=false\u0026amp;from_review_page=2\"\u003esee review\u003c/a\u003e\n    \u003c/div\u003e\n\n\n    \u003cdiv id='comments_for_review_22546263' style='display: none;'\u003e\n\u003cdiv class='brown_comment'\u003e\n\u003cspan class=\"loadingLinkSpan\"\u003e\u003ca class=\"loadingLink\" data-remote=\"true\" href=\"/review/22546263/comments?reverse=true\"\u003eView all 11 comments\u003c/a\u003e\u003cspan class=\"loadingAnimation\"\u003e\u003c/span\u003e\u003cspan class=\"loadingError\"\u003e\u003c/span\u003e\u003c/span\u003e\n\u003c/div\u003e\n\n\u003c/div\u003e\n\n  \u003c/td\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\n      \u003c/div\u003e\n\n  \u003c/div\u003e\n\n  \u003cdiv class=\"clear\"\u003e\u003c/div\u003e\n\u003c/div\u003e\n\n    \u003c/div\u003e\n  \u003c/div\u003e\n    \u003cdiv class=\"elementListBrownSeparator\"\u003e\u003c/div\u003e\n\n\n\n  \u003cdiv class=\"friendReviews elementListBrown\"\u003e\n    \u003cdiv class=\"section\"\u003e\n      \n\n\u003cdiv id=\"review_701426394\" class=\"review nosyndicate\" itemprop=\"reviews\" itemscope itemtype=\"http://schema.org/Review\"\u003e\n  \u003clink itemprop=\"url\" href=\"https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/701426394\" /\u003e\n  \u003ca title=\"Hunger For Knowledge\" class=\"left imgcol\" href=\"/user/show/23184292-hunger-for-knowledge\"\u003e\u003cimg alt=\"Hunger For Knowledge\" src=\"https://d.gr-assets.com/users/1433935192p2/23184292.jpg\" /\u003e\u003c/a\u003e\n\n  \u003cdiv class=\"left bodycol\"\u003e\n    \u003cdiv class=\"reviewHeader uitext stacked\"\u003e\n        \u003ca class=\"reviewDate createdAt right\" itemprop=\"publishDate\" href=\"/review/show/701426394?book_show_action=false\"\u003eMar 22, 2015\u003c/a\u003e\n\n      \u003ca title=\"Hunger For Knowledge\" class=\"user\" href=\"/user/show/23184292-hunger-for-knowledge\"\u003eHunger For Knowledge\u003c/a\u003e\n\n        rated it\n        \u003cspan class=\" staticStars\"\u003e\u003cspan title=\"it was ok\" size=\"15x15\" class=\"staticStar p10\"\u003eit was ok\u003c/span\u003e\u003cspan title=\"it was ok\" size=\"15x15\" class=\"staticStar p10\"\u003e\u003c/span\u003e\u003cspan title=\"it was ok\" size=\"15x15\" class=\"staticStar p0\"\u003e\u003c/span\u003e\u003cspan title=\"it was ok\" size=\"15x15\" class=\"staticStar p0\"\u003e\u003c/span\u003e\u003cspan title=\"it was ok\" size=\"15x15\" class=\"staticStar p0\"\u003e\u003c/span\u003e\u003c/span\u003e\n\n\n\n        \n\n\n          \u003cdiv class=\"uitext greyText bookshelves\"\u003e\n            Shelves:\n              \u003ca class=\"actionLinkLite\" href=\"/review/list/23184292-hunger-for-knowledge?shelf=physical-books-bought\"\u003ephysical-books-bought\u003c/a\u003e, \n              \u003ca class=\"actionLinkLite\" href=\"/review/list/23184292-hunger-for-knowledge?shelf=young-adult\"\u003eyoung-adult\u003c/a\u003e, \n              \u003ca class=\"actionLinkLite\" href=\"/review/list/23184292-hunger-for-knowledge?shelf=vampires\"\u003evampires\u003c/a\u003e, \n              \u003ca class=\"actionLinkLite\" href=\"/review/list/23184292-hunger-for-knowledge?shelf=reviewed\"\u003ereviewed\u003c/a\u003e\n          \u003c/div\u003e\n    \u003c/div\u003e\n\n\n        \u003cdiv class=\"reviewText stacked\"\u003e\n              \u003cspan id=\"reviewTextContainer701426394\" class=\"readable\" style=\"\"\u003e\n            \n\u003cspan id=\"freeTextContainer12466395011212942386\"\u003eI finally did it. I fully and completely read Twilight instead of just glancing it over, reading bits of here and there. Instead of settling with multiple, spoiler trapped reviews of it, I did it, and I did it fast.\u003cbr\u003e\u003cbr\u003eAs much as I do understand the problematics and complexity of this story, it is not what is my main issue with the whole Twilight saga. My problem lies in the shadows of what these books created on the big screen. Something tedious enough to make Robert Pattinson appearing as the most\u003c/span\u003e\n  \u003cspan id=\"freeText12466395011212942386\" style=\"display:none\"\u003eI finally did it. I fully and completely read Twilight instead of just glancing it over, reading bits of here and there. Instead of settling with multiple, spoiler trapped reviews of it, I did it, and I did it fast.\u003cbr\u003e\u003cbr\u003eAs much as I do understand the problematics and complexity of this story, it is not what is my main issue with the whole Twilight saga. My problem lies in the shadows of what these books created on the big screen. Something tedious enough to make Robert Pattinson appearing as the most sexiest, hottest, fuckable, swoon worthy vampire ever. Ever. ARGH. Just no. Please, seriously. \u003cbr\u003e\u003cbr\u003eJust the thought of that made me need some peace into my heart. \u003cbr\u003e\u003cbr\u003e\u003cimg src=\"https://i.gr-assets.com/images/S/photo.goodreads.com/hostedimages/1427055984i/14170785._SX540_.jpg\" class=\"escapedImg\"\u003e\u003cbr\u003e\u003cbr\u003eNow, that's better. That's sexy. That's hot. That's to fill my heart and soul with good, erotic vampire thoughts. I swoon for you, Gary Oldman.\u003cbr\u003e\u003cbr\u003eHowever, I don't want to talk about the negative feels but rather memorize the impact I know this book had to the people around me.\u003cbr\u003e\u003cbr\u003eI knew so many individuals who had never read anything outside their studies or work materials. I knew too many people who had no passion towards written word, no interest toward reading whatsoever. Despite of that, they chose to read Twilight because they did not want to miss out of this global phenomena, something that was on everyone's lips.\u003cbr\u003e\u003cbr\u003eIt is very hard to forget most reactions from them after finishing their read. The passion, the eagerness, the happiness, the excitement, the constant need to talk about their experience, how much they had loved the story, and the surprise of how they discovered the pleasure of enjoyable reading. \u003cbr\u003e\u003cbr\u003eThat. That is a great thing to witness. A great thing to see. \u003cbr\u003e\u003cbr\u003eI miss that feeling. The more I read, the more older I get, the less I experience it myself. The more great books I read, the more demanding I get, the more challenging it is with the emotions of amazing-sweaty-balls. It is still there, but not as often I would wish it to be.\u003cbr\u003e\u003cbr\u003eIt is easy to submit myself into a love-hate relationship with Twilight because as much as it annoys the shit out of me, I am not completely blind of its positive effects to others.\u003cbr\u003e\u003cbr\u003eAlso posted at: \u003ca target=\"_blank\" href=\"http://hfk.booklikes.com/\" rel=\"nofollow\"\u003ehttp://hfk.booklikes.com/\u003c/a\u003e\u003c/span\u003e\n  \u003ca data-text-id=\"12466395011212942386\" href=\"#\" onclick=\"swapContent($(this));; return false;\"\u003e...more\u003c/a\u003e\n\n          \u003c/span\u003e\n        \u003c/div\u003e\n\n\n      \u003cdiv class=\"reviewFooter uitext buttons\"\u003e\n        \n\n\u003ctr class=\"no_border feedFooterReview\" id=\"update_comment_stuff_Review701426394\"\u003e\n  \u003ctd colspan=\"2\"\u003e\n    \u003cdiv class=\"updateActionLinks\"\u003e\n        \u003ca class=\"right flag\" rel=\"nofollow\" id=\"flag_link701426394\" title=\"Flag this review as inappropriate.\" href=\"/flagged/new?resource_id=701426394\u0026amp;resource_type=Review\u0026amp;return_url=%2Fbook%2Fshow%2F41865.Twilight\"\u003eflag\u003c/a\u003e\n\n\n\n\n\n      \u003cspan class='likeItContainer' id='like_container_review_701426394'\u003e\u003ca id=\"like_count_review_701426394\" rel=\"nofollow\" href=\"/rating/voters/701426394?resource_type=Review\"\u003e\u003cspan class=\"likesCount\"\u003e52 likes\u003c/span\u003e\u003c/a\u003e\u0026nbsp;\u0026middot;\u0026nbsp;\u003ca rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"jsLike like_it gr-button gr-button--small\" href=\"https://www.goodreads.com/user/new?remember=true\u0026amp;return_url=%2Fbook%2Freviews%2F41865\"\u003eLike\u003c/a\u003e\u003c/span\u003e\u0026nbsp;\u0026middot;\u0026nbsp;\u003ca href=\"/review/show/701426394?book_show_action=false\u0026amp;from_review_page=2\"\u003esee review\u003c/a\u003e\n    \u003c/div\u003e\n\n\n    \u003cdiv id='comments_for_review_701426394' style='display: none;'\u0