s=\"staticStar p0\"\u003e\u003c/span\u003e\u003cspan title=\"did not like it\" size=\"15x15\" class=\"staticStar p0\"\u003e\u003c/span\u003e\u003c/span\u003e\n\n\n\n        \n\n\n          \u003cdiv class=\"uitext greyText bookshelves\"\u003e\n            Shelves:\n              \u003ca class=\"actionLinkLite\" href=\"/review/list/217454-kate?shelf=reviewed\"\u003ereviewed\u003c/a\u003e\n          \u003c/div\u003e\n    \u003c/div\u003e\n\n\n        \u003cdiv class=\"reviewText stacked\"\u003e\n              \u003cspan id=\"reviewTextContainer6192578\" class=\"readable\" style=\"\"\u003e\n            \n\u003cspan id=\"freeTextContainer6498898498147217162\"\u003e\u003cbr\u003eBook Review: Stephanie Meyer, Twilight (Atom, 2006, London)\u003cbr\u003e\u003cbr\u003eI read this book on recommendations from loads of people. I didn't think it sounded like I would enjoy it at first, but then I know not to judge a book too much by initial impressions.\u003cbr\u003e\u003cbr\u003eAnd I really wanted to like this, I did.\u003cbr\u003e\u003cbr\u003eBut I just can't.\u003cbr\u003e\u003cbr\u003eFirst, I've never been the kind of person that enjoys purple prose. Adjectives are all well and good, but when we get 'sparkled', 'like thousands of tiny diamonds', 'perfectly', 'sculpted, incandescen\u003c/span\u003e\n  \u003cspan id=\"freeText6498898498147217162\" style=\"display:none\"\u003e\u003cbr\u003eBook Review: Stephanie Meyer, Twilight (Atom, 2006, London)\u003cbr\u003e\u003cbr\u003eI read this book on recommendations from loads of people. I didn't think it sounded like I would enjoy it at first, but then I know not to judge a book too much by initial impressions.\u003cbr\u003e\u003cbr\u003eAnd I really wanted to like this, I did.\u003cbr\u003e\u003cbr\u003eBut I just can't.\u003cbr\u003e\u003cbr\u003eFirst, I've never been the kind of person that enjoys purple prose. Adjectives are all well and good, but when we get 'sparkled', 'like thousands of tiny diamonds', 'perfectly', 'sculpted, incandescent chest', 'scintillating', 'glistening, pale lavender lids', and finally 'a perfect statue, carved in some unknown stone, smooth like marble, glittering like crystal' all within one paragraph, it really takes the piss, to be honest.\u003cbr\u003e\u003cbr\u003ePart of me doesn't understand why this was published in the first place. But then, the concept works well enough, and badly written vampire novels do sell (Anne Rice, anyone?)\u003cbr\u003e\u003cbr\u003ePart of the problem is that I find myself unable to root for the characters. Bella began the story depressed, angsting over what turned out to be the fact that she'd left home for no apparent reason. She ends the story without having learned anything from her experiences.\u003cbr\u003e\u003cbr\u003eEdward is over one hundred years old, I don't care if he looks young, he's still with a seventeen year old girl. It's irresponsible. Like Bella, he doesn't appear to learn from his many mistakes.\u003cbr\u003e\u003cbr\u003eSomething I found particularly nasty was when Bella turned down three dates to the dance, only to pawn those dates off on so-called friends. Low. I mean, put yourself in Jessica's position: how must that feel?\u003cbr\u003e\u003cbr\u003eI could go on and on about the reasons these characters make me want to stab them, but I won't.\u003cbr\u003e\u003cbr\u003eMeyer had an opportunity here, with this concept, to show the obsessive, all-consuming thing that first love can be in an interesting way. Would Bella being bitten, transformed not signify a loss of innocence better than simply sleeping in Edward's arms?\u003cbr\u003e\u003cbr\u003eAnother problem I had was that there only seemed to be a plot in the opening stage and the final one hundred pages. It was almost as if the author took the middle 200 pages to indulge in her own creations and fantasies without any real development.\u003c/span\u003e\n  \u003ca data-text-id=\"6498898498147217162\" href=\"#\" onclick=\"swapContent($(this));; return false;\"\u003e...more\u003c/a\u003e\n\n          \u003c/span\u003e\n        \u003c/div\u003e\n\n\n      \u003cdiv class=\"reviewFooter uitext buttons\"\u003e\n        \n\n\u003ctr class=\"no_border feedFooterReview\" id=\"update_comment_stuff_Review6192578\"\u003e\n  \u003ctd colspan=\"2\"\u003e\n    \u003cdiv class=\"updateActionLinks\"\u003e\n        \u003ca class=\"right flag\" rel=\"nofollow\" id=\"flag_link6192578\" title=\"Flag this review as inappropriate.\" href=\"/flagged/new?resource_id=6192578\u0026amp;resource_type=Review\u0026amp;return_url=%2Fbook%2Fshow%2F41865.Twilight\"\u003eflag\u003c/a\u003e\n\n\n\n\n\n      \u003cspan class='likeItContainer' id='like_container_review_6192578'\u003e\u003ca id=\"like_count_review_6192578\" rel=\"nofollow\" href=\"/rating/voters/6192578?resource_type=Review\"\u003e\u003cspan class=\"likesCount\"\u003e52 likes\u003c/span\u003e\u003c/a\u003e\u0026nbsp;\u0026middot;\u0026nbsp;\u003ca rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"jsLike like_it gr-button gr-button--small\" href=\"https://www.goodreads.com/user/new?remember=true\u0026amp;return_url=%2Fbook%2Freviews%2F41865\"\u003eLike\u003c/a\u003e\u003c/span\u003e\u0026nbsp;\u0026middot;\u0026nbsp;\u003ca href=\"/review/show/6192578?book_show_action=false\u0026amp;from_review_page=2\"\u003esee review\u003c/a\u003e\n    \u003c/div\u003e\n\n\n    \u003cdiv id='comments_for_review_6192578' style='display: none;'\u003e\n\u003cdiv class='brown_comment'\u003e\n\u003cspan class=\"loadingLinkSpan\"\u003e\u003ca class=\"loadingLink\" data-remote=\"true\" href=\"/review/6192578/comments?reverse=true\"\u003eView all 17 comments\u003c/a\u003e\u003cspan class=\"loadingAnimation\"\u003e\u003c/span\u003e\u003cspan class=\"loadingError\"\u003e\u003c/span\u003e\u003c/span\u003e\n\u003c/div\u003e\n\n\u003c/div\u003e\n\n  \u003c/td\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\n      \u003c/div\u003e\n\n  \u003c/div\u003e\n\n  \u003cdiv class=\"clear\"\u003e\u003c/div\u003e\n\u003c/div\u003e\n\n    \u003c/div\u003e\n  \