n title=\"liked it\" size=\"15x15\" class=\"staticStar p10\"\u003e\u003c/span\u003e\u003cspan title=\"liked it\" size=\"15x15\" class=\"staticStar p0\"\u003e\u003c/span\u003e\u003cspan title=\"liked it\" size=\"15x15\" class=\"staticStar p0\"\u003e\u003c/span\u003e\u003c/span\u003e\n\n          \u003cspan class=\"greyText\"\u003e\u0026nbsp;\u0026middot;\u0026nbsp;\u003c/span\u003e\n          \u003ca class=\"lightGreyText\" title=\"Paperback 9780316058988\" href=\"/book/show/12024.Twilight\"\u003ereview of another edition\u003c/a\u003e\n\n\n          \u003cdiv\u003e\n    \u003cspan class=\"greyText\"\u003eRecommended to J by: \u003c/span\u003e\n      Everyone\n  \u003c/div\u003e\n\n\n\n    \u003c/div\u003e\n\n\n        \u003cdiv class=\"reviewText stacked\"\u003e\n              \u003cspan id=\"reviewTextContainer31373968\" class=\"readable\" style=\"\"\u003e\n            \n\u003cspan id=\"freeTextContainer14806631957804539571\"\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eAFORE-\u003c/strong\u003e Fine. Fine. Fine. I'll read it. I have two things to say first:\u003cbr\u003e\u003cbr\u003e1) I am annoyed this woman can not spell her own name and have very low expectations based on that fact.\u003cbr\u003e2) The vampires better be exciting.\u003cbr\u003e\u003cbr\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eAFTER-\u003c/strong\u003e \u003cem\u003eI could still feel warmth where his skin touched mine. The moisture of his lips was on my throat and the silken bristles of his hair brushed over my face as he drew his mouth down. The smell of him lingered in my nostrils. It was not like flowers.\u003cbr\u003e\u003cbr\u003eI wanted him to bite me. Instead he p\u003c/em\u003e\u003c/span\u003e\n  \u003cspan id=\"freeText14806631957804539571\" style=\"display:none\"\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eAFORE-\u003c/strong\u003e Fine. Fine. Fine. I'll read it. I have two things to say first:\u003cbr\u003e\u003cbr\u003e1) I am annoyed this woman can not spell her own name and have very low expectations based on that fact.\u003cbr\u003e2) The vampires better be exciting.\u003cbr\u003e\u003cbr\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eAFTER-\u003c/strong\u003e \u003cem\u003eI could still feel warmth where his skin touched mine. The moisture of his lips was on my throat and the silken bristles of his hair brushed over my face as he drew his mouth down. The smell of him lingered in my nostrils. It was not like flowers.\u003cbr\u003e\u003cbr\u003eI wanted him to bite me. Instead he pulled his head up and looked at me curiously. No question came, but I knew he was trying to understand. Trying to see what had brought me to this place. He looked like a cat with his head slightly cocked, as though listening for the words I couldn’t dare to utter. He was beautiful. Dark eyes aglitter, cunning written plainly on his face. Then the cat became a tiger. \u003cbr\u003e\u003cbr\u003e“Get up.” The dream memory broke off and I opened my eyes. The tiger was alive and pacing. “Get up. NOW.” I scrambled to the other side of the wide bed, finally afraid. Two thoughts clicked into place simultaneously: \u003cbr\u003e\u003cbr\u003eThis is what he’d warned me of. \u003cbr\u003eHe’d been watching me sleep.\u003cbr\u003e\u003cbr\u003eAnd there was no hope for me. No escape. I was alone with this beautiful man and this ravenous beast and the danger was of my own design. He’d tried to tell me but, headstrong and foolish, I didn’t believe. And now, when I believed it to the very core of my being, there was no escape. Not that I’d have wanted one anyway.\u003c/em\u003e\u003cbr\u003e\u003cbr\u003eI am such a girl.\u003cbr\u003eYeah. So \u003cem\u003eTwilight.\u003c/em\u003e I’m going to say something here that a few of you may hate me for. This book is not well written. It’s just not. Meyer’s a storyteller but this is not great literature. The typos I grumbled about? I wasn’t complaining so much about the typos themselves – okay, I kind of was - but what really bothered me was the type of typos. It’s clear someone has actually done some editing, but to improve the writing rather than to add a dropped period or correct a misspelling. It didn’t help.\u003cbr\u003e\u003cbr\u003eAnd yet I enjoyed the book. I am such a girl. This is, I am convinced, where Meyer has struck the mother lode. Edward is handsome. Beautiful even. A marble statue of masculine beauty. I hesitate to say hot because the fact is he’s not. He’s cold to the touch, which makes him all the more attractive because he’s a challenge. Untouchable, so obviously all I can think of is touching him. Did I mention he’s handsome? And he likes me. Me! He spends pages and pages and pages fighting down his attraction to me but I’m so sweet smelling, so delicious, so special, he just can’t. I’m his own brand of heroin. More dreaminess: Edward’s beauteous \u003cem\u003eand\u003c/em\u003e smart. Brains are sexy. Can I get an ‘Amen’? But so is brawn and Edward’s as agile and athletically gifted as he is beautiful. Did I already say he’s beautiful? Sorry. It’s just that he’s \u003cem\u003esooo\u003c/em\u003e beautiful. And rich. And he likes me. Me! And he’s bad. But he’s good. He’s fighting his bad side because he’s so good and he likes me. Me! I must really be special.\u003cbr\u003e\u003cbr\u003eAnd there it is. Special. We girls like to be made to feel special. Like we’re the only one. The only one whose mind he can’t read and the only one whose mind he wants to read. The only girl he could spend all day talking to and still want to spend tomorrow with. The only girl he’s ever kissed. I’m so extraordinarily special that he’s fighting his very nature for me. Never forget Edward is a vampire. He’s dangerous. C’mon, you know you like it. And he likes \u003cem\u003eme\u003c/em\u003e so much he’d like to feast on me. But I’m (almost, maybe, not quite) safe because he’ll protect me from himself. \u003cem\u003e\"And so the lion fell in love with the lamb. What a stupid lamb. What a sick, masochistic lion.\"\u003c/em\u003e Aww… He loves me…\u003cbr\u003e\u003cbr\u003e\u003cem\u003e* sigh *\u003c/em\u003e\u003cbr\u003e\u003cbr\u003eAnyway. Points given for bringing my teenage daydreams to life. Points taken away for making my hero a vampire. Points given for writing a long book. Points taken for filling several pages of it with a girl googling and sending emails to her mother. Points given for not including sex in my teenage vampire love story. Points taken away for not including sex in my adult vampire love story. Points given for creativity. (Vampires sparkle in the sunlight??) Points taken for trying to undo hundreds of years worth of vampire lore in a mere 480 pages. (Several of which have been wasted on google searches for “vampire”.) What does that tally up to? I’d say three stars and two fang marks. Cause I really wanted him to bite.\u003cbr\u003e\u003c/span\u003e\n  \u003ca data-text-id=\"14806631957804539571\" href=\"#\" onclick=\"swapContent($(this));; return false;\"\u003e...more\u003c/a\u003e\n\n          \u003c/span\u003e\n        \u003c/div\u003e\n\n\n      \u003cdiv class=\"reviewFooter uitext buttons\"\u003e\n        \n\n\u003ctr class=\"no_border feedFooterReview\" id=\"update_comment_stuff_Review31373968\"\u003e\n  \u003ctd colspan=\"2\"\u003e\n    \u003cdiv class=\"updateActionLinks\"\u003e\n        \u003ca class=\"right flag\" rel=\"nofollow\" id=\"flag_link31373968\" title=\"Flag this review as inappropriate.\" href=\"/flagged/new?resource_id=31373968\u0026amp;resource_type=Review\u0026amp;return_url=%2Fbook%2Fshow%2F41865.Twilight\"\u003eflag\u003c/a\u003e\n\n\n\n\n\n      \u003cspan class='likeItContainer' id='like_container_review_31373968'\u003e\u003ca id=\"like_count_review_31373968\" rel=\"nofollow\" href=\"/rating/voters/31373968?resource_type=Review\"\u003e\u003cspan class=\"likesCount\"\u003e49 likes\u003c/span\u003e\u003c/a\u003e\u0026nbsp;\u0026middot;\u0026nbsp;\u003ca rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"jsLike like_it gr-button gr-button--small\" href=\"https://www.goodreads.com/user/new?remember=true\u0026amp;return_url=%2Fbook%2Freviews%2F41865\"\u003eLike\u003c/a\u003e\u003c/span\u003e\u0026nbsp;\u0026middot;\u0026nbsp;\u003ca href=\"/review/show/31373968?book_show_action=false\u0026amp;from_review_page=2\"\u003esee review\u003c/a\u003e\n    \u003c/div\u003e\n\n\n    \u003cdiv id='comments_for_review_31373968' style='display: none;'\u003e\n\u003cdiv class='brown_comment'\u003e\n\u003cspan class=\"loadingLinkSpan\"\u003e\u003ca class=\"loadingLink\" data-remote=\"true\" href=\"/review/31373968/comments?reverse=true\"\u003eView all 28 comments\u003c/a\u003e\u003cspan class=\"loadingAnimation\"\u003e\u003c/span\u003e\u003cspan class=\"loadingError\"\u003e\u003c/span\u003e\u003c/span\u003e\n\u003c/div\u003e\n\n\u003c/div\u003e\n\n  \u003c/td\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\n      \u003c/div\u003e\n\n  \u003c/div\u003e\n\n  \u003cdiv class=\"clear\"\u003e\u003c/div\u003e\n\u003c/div\u003e\n\n    \u003c/div\u003e\n  \u003c/div\u003e\n    \u003cdiv class=\"elementListBrownSeparator\"\u003e\u003c/div\u003e\n\n\n\n  \u003cdiv class=\"friendReviews elementListBrown\"\u003e\n    \u003cdiv class=\"section\"\u003e\n      \n\n\u003cdiv id=\"review_53141696\" class=\"review nosyndicate\" itemprop=\"reviews\" itemscope itemtype=\"http://schema.org/Review\"\u003e\n  \u003clink itemprop=\"url\" href=\"https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/53141696\" /\u003e\n  \u003ca title=\"RandomAnthony\" class=\"left imgcol\" href=\"/user/show/721021-randomanthony\"\u003e\u003cimg alt=\"RandomAnthony\" src=\"https://d.gr-assets.com/users/1412821888p2/721021.jpg\" /\u003e\u003c/a\u003e\n\n  \u003cdiv class=\"left bodycol\"\u003e\n    \u003cdiv class=\"reviewHeader uitext stacked\"\u003e\n        \u003ca class=\"reviewDate createdAt right\" itemprop=\"publishDate\" href=\"/review/show/53141696?book_show_action=false\"\u003eDec 03, 2013\u003c/a\u003e\n\n      \u003ca title=\"RandomAnthony\" class=\"user\" href=\"/user/show/721021-randomanthony\"\u003eRandomAnthony\u003c/a\u003e\n\n        rated it\n        \u003cspan class=\" staticStars\"\u003e\u003cspan title=\"liked it\" size=\"15x15\" class=\"staticStar p10\"\u003eliked it\u003c/span\u003e\u003cspan title=\"liked it\" size=\"15x15\" class=\"staticStar p10\"\u003e\u003c/span\u003e\u003cspan title=\"liked it\" size=\"15x15\" class=\"staticStar p10\"\u003e\u003c/span\u003e\u003cspan title=\"liked it\" size=\"15x15\" class=\"staticStar p0\"\u003e\u003c/span\u003e\u003cspan title=\"liked it\" size=\"15x15\" class=\"staticStar p0\"\u003e\u003c/span\u003e\u003c/span\u003e\n\n\n\n        \n\n\n    \u003c/div\u003e\n\n\n        \u003cdiv class=\"reviewText stacked\"\u003e\n              \u003cspan id=\"reviewTextContainer53141696\" class=\"readable\" style=\"\"\u003e\n            \n\u003cspan id=\"freeTextContainer4718476506869025316\"\u003eMY THOUGHTS ON \u003cem\u003eTWILIGHT\u003c/em\u003e A TO Z, TEEN MAGAZINE STYLE…\u003cbr\u003e\u003cbr\u003e(I thought about hitting the “spoilers” tags, but there’s nothing revealed below that you don’t know if you’ve been paying even mild attention to the Bella/Edward phenomenon.)\u003cbr\u003e\u003cbr\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eA\u003c/strong\u003ewkward Action. The mad rush, in the last third of the book, to create some dramatic tension seems to come out of nowhere and isn’t always very, um, thoughtful, I guess. However, maybe in the world where vampires and human interact (or not) these slam-bang conflicts emerge\u003c/span\u003e\n  \u003cspan id=\"freeText4718476506869025316\" style=\"display:none\"\u003eMY THOUGHTS ON \u003cem\u003eTWILIGHT\u003c/em\u003e A TO Z, TEEN MAGAZINE STYLE…\u003cbr\u003e\u003cbr\u003e(I thought about hitting the “spoilers” tags, but there’s nothing revealed below that you don’t know if you’ve been paying even mild attention to the Bella/Edward phenomenon.)\u003cbr\u003e\u003cbr\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eA\u003c/strong\u003ewkward Action. The mad rush, in the last third of the book, to create some dramatic tension seems to come out of nowhere and isn’t always very, um, thoughtful, I guess. However, maybe in the world where vampires and human interact (or not) these slam-bang conflicts emerge. I can’t say.\u003cbr\u003e\u003cbr\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eB\u003c/strong\u003eella. Edward gets too much attention. Bella’s a better character. She’s smart, isolative, insecure, forthright, reserved, confusing, well, everything a teenage girl can be. I imagine every woman can relate to Bella’s attempts to navigate a, ahem, challenging relationship. I like Bella. She’d be a good kid to have around the neighborhood.\u003cbr\u003e\u003cbr\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eC\u003c/strong\u003eullen family. I suppose you can’t develop every character equally, and maybe you get more on each of them in the sequels, but the Cullens (outside of Edward) were as cardboard as they come, esp. Esme, who seems interesting but hardly speaks. And what’s the deal with Emmett? And Carlisle? I want to know. And what about that one who hates Bella? I can’t even remember her name, she’s so unimportant to the story.\u003cbr\u003e\u003cbr\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eD\u003c/strong\u003eoubt. These two fall in love awfully quickly, and the doubt/fear about some pretty heady issues gets resolved in literally a couple days. Now, one could argue that’s how teenage love develops, but I don’t know I agree.\u003cbr\u003e\u003cbr\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eE\u003c/strong\u003edward. You know what I find fascinating about Edward? I think, if you pay attention to Edward, you might learn something about what women/girls like in some guys. Edward is not a predictable doormat wuss. He gets angry, jealous, and petulant (you think he’d grow out of that, but he says this is a new experience). Bella doesn’t always get her way with him. But he’s gorgeous (as the author says, oh, about 11,000 times) and loyal. Gentlemen, pay attention to Edward. He may lead the way. He’s like a goth Zac Ephron.\u003cbr\u003e\u003cbr\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eF\u003c/strong\u003eorks. I could live in Forks. I like the natural, familiar rhythms of the town, how everyone seems to know each other without any typical “book small town” hokeyness. I bet the real estate is cheap, too.\u003cbr\u003e\u003cbr\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eG\u003c/strong\u003eordian knot. Bella and Edward’s relationship.\u003cbr\u003e\u003cbr\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eH\u003c/strong\u003eigh school. The author does an admirable job of walking the characters through Forks’ secondary school days. No one broke into dance. The kids were pretty good, for the most part, but engaged in regular petty intrigue. Realistic, I would say.\u003cbr\u003e\u003cbr\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eI\u003c/strong\u003emmortal. I can understand Bella’s desire for immortality. But how much do we really know about Bella? I mean, there’s more there, of course, because of what Edward can’t do (get your mind out of the gutter, pervs, not that) to her. \u003cbr\u003e\u003cbr\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eJ\u003c/strong\u003eacob is another interesting character that seems as if he’ll be important in a later book. He’s more Bella that Edward, slightly dorky and charming, more human (um, literally and metaphorically) and approachable. \u003cbr\u003e\u003cbr\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eK\u003c/strong\u003eiss. Did they ever actually kiss, full-on? It’s hard to tell. I think they did, but the author gets a little flowery when Bella and Edward touch. I don’t get the whole “abstinence” controversy. I don’t think this book is a covert “don’t have sex” tract.\u003cbr\u003e\u003cbr\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eL\u003c/strong\u003eoyalty, a major theme in the book. Should Bella and Edward be loyal to each other? Should the Cullens remain loyal to Edward, and Edward loyal to the Cullens? \u003cbr\u003e\u003cbr\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eM\u003c/strong\u003eind control. Ok, if vampires have all these tools to inherently attract victims, how can Bella be so sure she actually loves him and just isn’t, you know, falling for his tricks?\u003cbr\u003e\u003cbr\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eN\u003c/strong\u003eative Americans, who seem to have cut a deal with the Cullens and probably play a bigger role in the sequels.\u003cbr\u003e\u003cbr\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eO\u003c/strong\u003eld. Edward’s got, ahem, an age issue with Bella. He’s older than her. Does that make a difference? How come he still acts like kind of a brat?\u003cbr\u003e\u003cbr\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eP\u003c/strong\u003erom. I don’t care what Edward says, if she said she didn’t want to go, he shouldn’t make her go.\u003cbr\u003e\u003cbr\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eQ\u003c/strong\u003euestions unanswered. How did the Cullens stay hidden in Phoenix? I thought Phoenix was sunny all the time. And how come the schools never protested when the Cullens skipped school? Was it the mind control crap? \u003cbr\u003e\u003cbr\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eR\u003c/strong\u003eules. Throw all the traditional vampire rules into the dumpster. Holy water fails to make an appearance.\u003cbr\u003e\u003cbr\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eS\u003c/strong\u003eex. Yes, Bella asks if they can do it. You know she wants to.\u003cbr\u003e\u003cbr\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eT\u003c/strong\u003easte. Apparently Bella is all kinds of tasty to the vampires. She’s like a 3AM burrito wearing tight jeans and the best perfume ever.\u003cbr\u003e\u003cbr\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eU\u003c/strong\u003enique versus universal. This is where the author shines…she makes Bella sound like a unique, fascinating individual while also leaving just about any reader with elements to which she could relate. I give Meyer credit for her characterizations, and it’s not just Bella, but Charlie, the high school kids, etc. She only drops the ball with the vampires (outside of Edward, of course).\u003cbr\u003e\u003cbr\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eW\u003c/strong\u003eashington. Do you think the people of Washington are sick of people thinking the state is rainy all the time? I don’t think this book is going to do wonders for tourism.\u003cbr\u003e\u003cbr\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eV\u003c/strong\u003eirgins? I’m guessin’ yes.\u003cbr\u003e\u003cbr\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eX\u003c/strong\u003eenophobia. The Cullens do what they can to avoid being outsiders, but pretty much fail. There’s an X-Men feel to this part of the book.\u003cbr\u003e\u003cbr\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eY\u003c/strong\u003eouth. Edward’s technically older than Charlie. I can’t get my head around this. I know I said this before, but it’s a major problem in the book. You think Edward would, you know, learn something over the years, but he still sounds seventeen.\u003cbr\u003e\u003cbr\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eZ\u003c/strong\u003eealous readers. Do I want to read the next one? Maybe. I liked the movie, even though Kim says the film version “sucks ass”. I’m curious about this whole Jacob thing and where that might lead. And I still don’t know what in the hell is going on with Bella and her evident, if passive, powers. So, like I said, maybe. \u003cem\u003eTwilight\u003c/em\u003e isn’t as smart or well-researched as \u003cem\u003eOutlander\u003c/em\u003e, the last book of this nature I read, but I think it’s more fun and definitely an easier read. I think it’s fair to ask anti-Twilight factions to get over themselves…the book may be more popcorn than arthouse, but it’s decent. I can understand the book’s appeal at the same time I feel like I still have a lot to learn about what women like about guys like Edward. And if I’m thinking that much after reading a book about vampires and teenage girls, well, the time was well spent. If \u003cem\u003eTwilight\u003c/em\u003e falls into your lap, it’s worth a couple hours of your time.\u003cbr\u003e\u003cbr\u003e\u003cbr\u003e\u003cbr\u003e\u003cbr\u003e\u003c/span\u003e\n  \u003ca data-text-id=\"4718476506869025316\" href=\"#\" onclick=\"swapContent($(this));; return false;\"\u003e...more\u003c/a\u003e\n\n          \u003c/span\u003e\n        \u003c/div\u003e\n\n\n      \u003cdiv class=\"reviewFooter uitext buttons\"\u003e\n        \n\n\u003ctr cla